  "prompt": "How much does it cost to register a trademark in the U.S.?",
  "response": "The cost to register a trademark in the U.S. varies depending on several factors, but here's a breakdown of the main costs you'll encounter:\n\n**1. Application Fees (Paid to the USPTO - United States Patent and Trademark Office):**\n\n*   **TEAS Plus:** This is the cheapest option and the most common. It requires you to:\n    *   File online through the TEAS (Trademark Electronic Application System) Plus form.\n    *   Use a pre-approved list of goods and services (the USPTO's ID Manual).\n    *   Pay the fee for each class of goods and services.\n    *   Communicate with the USPTO electronically.\n    *   **Fee:** **$250 per class of goods/services.**\n*   **TEAS Standard:** This is more flexible than TEAS Plus, allowing you to write your own description of goods and services.\n    *   File online through the TEAS Standard form.\n    *   **Fee:** **$350 per class of goods/services.**\n\n    *A class of goods/services refers to the category in which you would like to register your trademark. For example, if you sell clothing and also offer online retail services, you would need to file in two different classes. This will increase the overall cost.*\n\n**2. Attorney Fees (Optional, but Highly Recommended):**\n\n*   **This is where the biggest variation in cost occurs.** Trademark attorneys can handle the entire process for you, from searching for existing trademarks to responding to USPTO office actions.\n*   **Cost:** Can range from **$500 to $3000+** for the entire process (search, application preparation, and prosecution), depending on the complexity and the attorney's experience. Some attorneys charge hourly, while others charge a flat fee.\n\n**3. Other Potential Costs:**\n\n*   **Trademark Search:** While not required by the USPTO, conducting a comprehensive trademark search before filing is *highly recommended*. This helps you determine if there are any existing trademarks that are similar to yours and could prevent you from registering your mark.  An attorney can do this, or you can use online search services.\n    *   **Cost:** Attorney-conducted search: **$500 - $1500+**.  DIY online search services: **$50 - $300+**, depending on the depth and features.\n*   **Response to Office Actions:** If the USPTO raises objections to your application (e.g., due to a conflicting trademark), you'll need to respond with arguments and evidence. This is called an \"Office Action.\"  An attorney is *highly recommended* for this.\n    *   **Cost:** Attorney fees can range from **$500 - $2000+ per office action**, depending on the complexity.\n*   **Statement of Use (SOU) Fee (if filing an Intent-to-Use Application):** If you're filing an \"intent-to-use\" application (meaning you haven't started using the trademark in commerce yet), you'll need to file a Statement of Use once you actually start using the mark.\n    *   **Fee:** **$100 per class of goods/services.**\n*   **Maintenance Fees:** Trademark registrations are not permanent. You need to pay maintenance fees at specific intervals to keep your registration active (typically around years 5-6, 9-10, and every 10 years thereafter).\n    *   **Maintenance Fees:** **Varying amounts per class, typically around $525 - $625.** You can find the current fees on the USPTO website.\n\n**Summary Table (Estimated Range):**\n\n| Expense                | Cost Range                                        |\n| ---------------------- | ------------------------------------------------- |\n| USPTO Application Fee (per class) | $250 (TEAS Plus) - $350 (TEAS Standard)                   |\n| Attorney Fees          | $500 - $3000+ (full process)                      |\n| Trademark Search         | $50 - $1500+                                       |\n| Office Action Response   | $500 - $2000+ per action                          |\n| Statement of Use Fee (per class)    | $100                                               |\n| Maintenance Fees (later years, per class) | ~$525-$625 |\n\n**Important Considerations:**\n\n*   **Complexity:** If your trademark is similar to existing marks or if your goods/services are complex, the costs (especially attorney fees) will likely be higher.\n*   **DIY vs. Attorney:** While it's possible to file a trademark application yourself, it's generally *not recommended*, especially if you're unfamiliar with trademark law. Mistakes can be costly and delay the process or even result in rejection of your application. An attorney can significantly increase your chances of success and protect your rights.\n*   **Multiple Classes:**  If your business involves goods or services in multiple classes, you will have to pay the filing fee for *each* class.\n\n**In conclusion:**\n\nThe *absolute minimum* cost to file a trademark application (using TEAS Plus and *without* an attorney) is **$250 per class of goods/services**.  However, to account for potential complications and significantly increase your chances of success, budgeting **$1500 - $5000+** is more realistic, especially if you hire an attorney.  The actual cost will depend on the specific circumstances of your application.\n",
